---
import Layout from '../layouts/BlogPost.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="About"
  description="A little about this corner of the internet."
  pubDate={new Date('2025-01-01')}
  heroImage="/blog-placeholder-about.jpg"
>
  <p>
    Welcome to this little corner of the internet — a place to think slowly, look carefully, and write about the cosmos and the questions it raises.
  </p>

  <p>
    Astronomy has a way of putting things in perspective. The light reaching us from distant galaxies left before our solar system existed. Black holes warp spacetime in ways our intuitions were never built to handle. And yet here we are, small and curious, peering up through an atmosphere that itself filters what we can see.
  </p>

  <h2>What this blog is</h2>

  <p>
    A journal, mostly. Observations on recent astronomy news, personal notes from nights spent under the sky, explorations of cosmological ideas, and occasional meditations on what it all might mean.
  </p>

  <p>
    Posts appear when something is worth saying, not on a schedule. Quality over cadence.
  </p>

  <h2>Tools of observation</h2>

  <p>
    This site is built with <a href="https://astro.build">Astro</a>, deployed via GitHub Pages, and written in plain Markdown. Fast, minimal, and focused on the words.
  </p>

  <h2>Get in touch</h2>

  <p>
    If something here resonated, sparked a question, or you want to share an observation of your own — you can reach me via the RSS feed or wherever you found this place.
  </p>

  <p style="font-style: italic; color: var(--text-secondary); font-family: var(--font-display); font-size: 1.1rem;">
    The universe is under no obligation to make sense to you.<br />— Neil deGrasse Tyson
  </p>
</Layout>